<h2>Powers of $1+\sqrt 7$</h2><div id="problem_icons" class="noprint"><a href="minimal=752"><img src="images/icons/file_html.png" title="Show HTML problem content" class="icon"></a>&nbsp;<span class="tooltip"><img src="images/icons/info.png" class="icon"><span class="tooltiptext_right">Published on Sunday, 21st March 2021, 01:00 am; Solved by 748;<br>Difficulty rating: 25%</span></span></div><div id="problem_info"><h3>Problem 752</h3></div>
<div class="problem_content" role="problem">
<p>
When $(1+\sqrt 7)$ is raised to an integral power, $n$, we always get a number of the form $(a+b\sqrt 7)$.<br>
We write $(1+\sqrt 7)^n = \alpha(n) + \beta(n)\sqrt 7$.
</p>
<p>
For a given number $x$ we  define $g(x)$ to be the smallest positive integer $n$ such that:
$$\begin{align}
\alpha(n) &amp;\equiv 1 \pmod x\qquad \text{and }\\
\beta(n) &amp;\equiv 0 \pmod x\end{align}
$$
and $g(x) = 0$ if there is no such value of $n$. For example, $g(3) = 0$, $g(5) = 12$.
</p>
<p>
Further define
$$ G(N) = \sum_{x=2}^N g(x)$$
You are given $G(10^2) = 28891$ and $G(10^3)  = 13131583$.
</p>
<p>
Find $G(10^6)$.
</p>
</div><br>
<br>
</div> <!--end_content-->

